      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why do cookie and cracker packaging lines need special conveyors?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Cookies and crackers are fragile products that break under impact, vibration, or compression. Standard conveyors create hard transfer points that crack products, build back-pressure during accumulation that crushes stacked products, and use belt surfaces that abrade coatings or decorations. Cookie and cracker lines use slip-torque conveyors, air-cushion transfers, and gentle accumulation zones to prevent breakage rates from exceeding 1-2%." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a counter stacker for cookies?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A counter stacker counts individual cookies, stacks them into a specified count (typically 5-20 cookies per slug), and delivers the slug to a wrapping machine. Counter stackers use photoeyes to count products on a high-speed belt, then divert counted groups onto a stacking conveyor where products align vertically or in shingle formation. Speeds range from 400 to 1,200+ cookies per minute per lane." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do you prevent cookie breakage on conveyors?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Prevent breakage by eliminating hard transfer points (use tapered nose rollers or zero-gap transfers), using slip-torque or low-friction accumulation (belt slips under stopped product instead of building pressure), maintaining gentle speed differentials between conveyor sections (no abrupt acceleration), and using soft belt surfaces that cushion impact. Target less than 2% breakage rate across the packaging line." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is slug-wrap packaging for cookies?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Slug-wrap packaging wraps a horizontal stack (slug) of cookies in a single film wrapper using a horizontal form-fill-seal (HFFS) machine. The slug conveyor delivers counted stacks of cookies on-edge to the wrapper infeed at precise spacing and speed. The wrapper applies film around the slug, seals longitudinally and at both ends, then cuts individual packages. This format is standard for sandwich cookies, thin crackers, and premium cookie brands." }
    }
  ]
};

